item.title: Hubble Probes the Black Hole Inside a Majestic Spiral Galaxy
item.dc:creator: cmolino
item.excerpt:encoded: The graceful, winding arms of the majestic spiral galaxy NGC 3147 appear like a grand spiral staircase sweeping through space in this Hubble Space Telescope image. They are actually long lanes of young blue stars, pinkish nebulas, and dust in silhouette.The beauty of the galaxy belies the fact that at its very center is a malnourished black hole surrounded by a thin, compact disk of stars, gas, and dust that have been caught up in a gravitational maelstrom. The black hole's gravity is so intense that anything that ventures near it gets swept up in the disk.The disk is so deeply embedded in the black hole's intense gravitational field that the light from the gas disk is modified, according to Einstein's theories of relativity, giving astronomers a unique peek at the dynamic processes close to a black hole.NGC 3147 is located 130 million light-years away in the northern circumpolar constellation Draco the Dragon.

Access to the Sunday School Building is limited to students and staff 10 a.m. to 12 p.m.

Safety Guidelines 

1. A sanitizing dispenser and masks will be available in the foyer.
2. When being seated in the chapel, we ask that you allow one empty chair between you and non-family members. You can sit next to the person accompanying you.
 
 We will   begin having Thursday evening meditation, book room sales, and juice socials  when we have enough volunteers to cover these activities.

____________________________________________________________________

Yogananda.org

also

Self Realization Fellowship's YouTube Channel

contains public classes, services, meditations and kirtans.

Please follow this link for information concerning closures. 

Wireless earphones are available for the hearing impaired.

Please ask an usher for more information.

 

__________________________________________________________________________________________________

 

About

Houston Center of Self-Realization Fellowship 

Welcome to the Houston Center of Self-Realization Fellowship, which serves families and friends in the greater Houston area through weekly devotional and meditation services. The Houston Center is composed of devoted local members and friends of Self-Realization Fellowship, a worldwide, non-profit religious organization founded by Paramahansa Yogananda in 1920 to teach scientific techniques of meditation that lead to a direct, personal experience of God. The Center is open to the public for services and special activities. You are invited to attend our services and welcome to stop by our bookroom to find out more about the teachings of Paramahansa Yogananda and our activities.

The meditation techniques taught by the fellowship are available in a series of lessons mailed from our international headquarters in Los Angeles, California. These lessons contain techniques of recharging the body, concentration, meditation, and the higher technique of Kriya Yoga, as well as instructions on how to live a balanced material and spiritual life.

As an introduction, we suggest that you read Paramahansa Yogananda's Autobiography of a Yogi. Copies of this spiritual classic are available in our Bookroom, in bookstores and public libraries, and is now available online.

item.title: Service Schedule
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded:
Sundays:

  • 9:40 - 10:00 AM:     Energization Exercises (Not Scheduled)
  • 10:00 - 10:45 AM:   Meditation
  • 11:00 - 12 noon:     Reading Service
  • 11:00 - 12 noon:     Sunday School
  • 11:00 - 12 noon:     Teen Group (first Sunday of each month)
Sunday School is offered for children ages 3 through 12. Sunday School presents Paramahansa Yogananda's how-to-live spiritual principles for children. We also have a nursery where younger children and their parents may enjoy the service. Teen Group presents Paramahansa Yogananda's how-to-live spiritual principles for teens ages 13 to 18 in the Morgan Building.

Mondays:

  • 7:00 -  9:00 PM:  Lesson Study Group (Not Scheduled)

Thursdays: (Not Scheduled)

  • 7:30 -  9:30  PM:  Meditation Service
  • 7:00 - 10:00 PM:  Meditation Service (first Thursday of the month)

Saturdays:

  • 8:00 AM –  1:00 PM: Day of Service on first Saturday of the month
  • 9:00 AM –  4:00 PM: Long Meditation on last Saturday of the month

  • (Not Scheduled) 

  • 12:00 PM –  3:00 PM: Open Meditation on all other Saturdays

    (Not Scheduled)

***Saturday schedule is subject to change to accommodate special events

Commemorative Services:

  • Birth of Paramahansa Yogananda—January 5th
  • Mahasamadhi of Paramahansa Yogananda—March 7th
  • Mahasamadhi of Swami Sri Yukteswar—March 9th
  • Birth of Swami Sri Yukteswar—May 10th
  • Babaji Day—July 25th
  • Janmashtami (Birth of Lord Krishna)—Aug/Sept (based on lunar calendar)
  • Mahasamadhi of Lahiri Mahasaya—September 26th
  • Birth of Lahiri Mahasaya—September 30th
Special services are held each year to honor the Self-Realization Fellowship gurus. They commemorate significant life events of each of the gurus. There are eight such services annually and are celebrated by SRF groups throughout the world. Each commemorative ceremony consists of prayers, short meditations, chanting, readings on the life and teachings of the master who is being celebrated, and a flower ceremony. The service lasts approximately one hour. For those who wish to prepare spiritually for the ceremony, there is an hour long meditation preceding the commemorative service. This meditation is open, and one can come and go quietly at any time. Devotees are asked to bring a flower, which will be used during the flower ceremony. It is a symbol of devotion to God and the SRF Gurus. In addition one is asked to bring a monetary donation in an envelope as a symbol of loyalty and faithfulness to the cause of Self-Realization Fellowship. These donations are forwarded to Mother Center (International headquarters in Los Angeles, CA) for the sharing of these sacred teachings with truth-seeking souls. These ceremonies are sacred and a beautiful expression of devotion toward the Gurus of Self-Realization Fellowship.  Paramahansa Yogananda said the following of the birthday of a master (which applies to all the special days):
"Celebration of the birthday of a God-realized soul should not be belittled as a merely social ceremony. It is a deeply spiritual occasion on which the vibrations of blessing from an illumined master are stronger than on other days in the year, because in the astral world, also, a celebration is taking place. Devotees who attend these birthday ceremonies with the right attitude will reap spiritual benefits and will find their high resolutions strengthened." -Paramahansa Yogananda
All are urged to attend these beautiful and spiritually uplifting ceremonies. They are an integral part of the many reading and meditations services provided by the Houston Center. In addition, we hold an all-day Christmas Meditation on a Saturday in December commemorating the birth of Lord Jesus. In early January there is a second all-day meditation honoring the birth of Paramahansa Yogananda. The meditations include periods of readings pertinent to the occasion as well as special music. Periods of meditation last from 3o to 45 minutes.

item.title: Frequently Asked Questions
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded:
For answers to questions that may not be on this list, you may find what you are looking for on the FAQ page of the SRF Main Website. Q: What is SRF?
A: Self-Realization Fellowship (SRF) is a worldwide, non-profit, religious organization with international headquarters in Los Angeles, California.  Self-Realization Fellowship was founded in 1920 by Paramahansa Yogananda for the purpose of dissemination of Kriya Yoga, a definite scientific technique for attaining direct personal experience of God.  Through its worldwide service and teachings, Self-Realization Fellowship seeks to awaken greater understanding of the harmony underlying all true religions, and a fuller expression in this world of the love that unites all people when they realize their oneness with God.  The weekly SRF Lessons are available to those who would like to study the teachings.
Q: I have just discovered SRF and the Houston Center.  Can I get more information about the Houston Center and what it offers?
A: Absolutely!  We are happy that you want to know more about SRF and our center.  Please browse our website, and hopefully you will find everything you need to know about us, including weekly services and gatherings.  Also, subscribing to our weekly announcements and quarterly newsletter are great ways for you to keep up with current events at the center.  If you have more specific information you would like to request that you cannot find on the website, please send an email to info@srfhouston.org, or fill out the email form in the Contact page, and someone will respond to your inquiry shortly.
Q: What activities does your center have during weekdays?
A: The Houston Center of SRF provides study groups for lessons students on Monday evenings, as well as meditation services on Thursday evenings.  For more information, please see our Service Schedule.
Q: What is "Day of Service"
A: The caring for the buildings and grounds is done by devotees on a volunteer basis.  Once a month, usually the first Saturday of the month, we have a day of service where devotees work on various maintenance projects.  The morning of activity is followed by a vegetarian lunch.
Q: Does the Houston Center of SRF offer any retreats?
A: Yes. Twice a year we reserve rooms at the Ruah Center of Villa de Matel in Houston for a silent retreat.  The retreat begins on Friday evening (Thursday evening arrival is optional) and continues through Sunday morning.  Rooms and meals are provided on a donation basis.  A number of group meditations are scheduled and there is plenty of free time to stroll about the grounds or visit the beautiful chapel.
Q: Does the Houston Center of SRF have items for purchase?
A: Yes. Our bookstore is located off the entry foyer in the main chapel.  SRF books, CDS, DVDs, and pictures in addition to meditation supplies are available for sale.  We accept all major forms of payment.  The bookstore is open after Sunday service.  If there is a healing or memorial service following the reading service, the bookstore is not open until after the service is concluded.
Q: What attire should visitors wear during services?
A: Any modest clothing that is loose fitting, comfortable, and adequately covers the body is acceptable.  Tight fitting clothing or anything that may come across as revealing or provocative should be avoided.

item.title: Welcome
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded:
Thank you for visiting the website of the Houston Center of Self-Realization Fellowship. I hope you will join us in exploring the timeless teachings of Paramahansa Yogananda and reclaim your oneness with God — ever new joy, love, and peace. It is through the meditation techniques taught by Self-Realization Fellowship that we can discover this divine consciousness that is hidden within each of us.
The meditation techniques are given in a series of home-study lessons sent from the international headquarter every two weeks. Thus step-by-step one can advance on the path of Self-realization by practicing the meditation techniques, which culminate with Kriya Yoga. Paramahansa Yogananda often referred to the Kriya Yoga path, with its scientific techniques of meditation, as “the highway to the Infinite.” He found the path of Kriya Yoga to be the most effective method of attaining the highest goal of religion, and indeed life itself: union with Bliss.
Our center has a variety of services open to all. Each includes prayers, readings from the works of Paramahansa Yogananda, chanting, and most importantly, meditation. In addition we have a Sunday school program for the young children and a teen group for those older. There are also social events where you can meet devotees and learn more about Self-Realization Fellowship and the Houston Center.
Please continue to explore our website. You will find detailed information on our services, a brief history of our group, where to get our quarterly newsletter, literature that is available, including Paramahansa Yogananda's spiritual classic Autobiography of a Yogi, and how to subscribe to the all-important Self-Realization Fellowship Lessons.
We hope you find our website informative.
In Divine Friendship,
Houston Center of Self-Realization Fellowship

item.title: Introduction
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded:
Introduction to The Houston Center

3425 Golf Drive, Houston, TX 77018-6225 Phone: 713-262-7272 http://www.srfhouston.org; Email: info@srfhouston.org

Welcome to the Houston Center. The center is a part of Self-Realization Fellowship, a nonprofit religious organization with international headquarters in Los Angeles, CA. Self-Realization Fellowship was founded in 1920 by Paramahansa Yogananda for the purpose of dissemination of Kriya Yoga, a definite scientific technique for attaining direct personal experience of God. Through its worldwide service and teachings, Self-Realization Fellowship seeks to awaken greater understanding of the harmony underlying all true religions, and a fuller expression in this world of the love that unites all people when they realize their oneness with God. The SRF Lessons are available to those who would like to study the teachings. The center has a number of services and activities, which are listed below. Sunday Service: Each Sunday there is a service in the chapel from 11:00 AM to noon. It includes periods of chanting, short meditations, readings from the Bible and Bhagavad Gita, and a reading taken from the writings of Paramahansa Yogananda. It is preceded by a meditation service from 10:00 to 10:45 AM. Sunday School: Sunday school for children ages 4 to 12 is held in the Sunday school building at the same time as the Sunday service. For younger children we have a parent-infant room in the Sunday school building where a parent may attend to the child while watching the Sunday service on closed-circuit TV. On the first Sunday of the month the teen group (ages 13 to 18) meets from 11:00 to 12:00. Bookstore: A bookstore is located off the foyer in the chapel. SRF books, CDS, DVDs, and pictures in addition to meditation supplies are available for sale, in addition to cash or checks, credit cards are accepted. The bookstore is open between the Sunday meditation and Sunday service and after the Sunday service. Meditation Services: In addition to the meditation held before the reading service on Sunday, there are a number of services in the chapel dedicated exclusively to meditation. Every Thursday evening a meditation services is held from 7:30 to 9:30 (7:00 to 10:00 on the first Thursday of the month). On the fourth Saturday of each month there is an all-day meditation from 9 AM to 4 PM. The chapel is open from noon to 3 PM for meditation on Saturdays when the chapel is not in use. There are a number of special meditations throughout the year — New Year's Eve meditation, Good Friday meditation, an all-day Christmas meditation, and a special all-day meditation in early January honoring Paramahansa Yogananda. All are welcome. Lesson Study Group: Every Monday evening from 7:00 to 8:00 there is a lesson study group in the chapel. Devotees take turns reading a paragraph from an SRF lesson. After each reading, there is a brief meditation to assimilate that part of the teaching. The study group is followed by a meditation from 8:00 to 9:00. The lesson study group is open to all SRF lesson students. Bhagavad Gita Study Group: On the third Sunday of each month devotees meet in the chapel at 12:30 for an hour to read from God Talks with Arjuna — Paramahansa Yogananda's translation of and commentary on the Bhagavad Gita. The format is the same as for the Lesson Study Group. All are welcome. Commemorative Services: Eight times a year on the birthday or anniversary of the passing of one of our gurus, we hold a special service at the chapel starting at 8:00 PM. There are several short meditations, chanting, and a reading pertaining to the guru whose anniversary is being celebrated. There is a flower ceremony where each devotee places a flower and donation in front of the Master's picture. All who are familiar with the guru-disciple relationship are welcome to attend. The service is preceded by a meditation from 7:00 to 7:45 PM. The services are:

January 5: Birthday of Paramahansa Yogananda

March 7: Mahasamadhi* of Paramahansa Yogananda

March 9: Mahasamadhi* of Swami Sri Yukteswar

May 10: Birthday of Swami Sri Yukteswar

July 25: Babaji Day

Date varies: Janmashtami (Birthday of Lord Krishna)

September 26: Mahasamadhi* of Lahiri Mahasaya

September 30th: Birthday of Lahiri Mahasaya

* Mahasamadhi is the union of the soul with the Infinite during a God-realized yogi's final exit from the physical body. Retreats: Twice a year we reserve rooms at the Ruah Center of Villa de Matel in Houston for a silent retreat. The retreat begins on Thursday (Friday arrival optional) and continues through Sunday morning. Rooms and meals are provided on a donation basis. A number of group meditations are scheduled and SRF videos are shown. There is plenty of free time for private meditations, to stroll about the grounds, or to visit the chapel. Social Events: After Sunday service there is a juice social in the Sunday school building. Juice and light refreshments are provided. For Easter, Thanksgiving, and Christmas we hold vegetarian potluck luncheons in the Sunday school building following the Sunday service. The juice socials and potlucks are a great way to get to know other devotees and to learn more about the Houston Center and SRF. Young-At-Heart Group: A group for young adults and those young at heart. The group meets for various activities, such as picnics. It's a good way to meet other young people who are on the SRF path. Monastic Visits: Once or twice a year we are blessed with a visit of SRF monks from Mother Center in Los Angeles, CA. These visits include classes, group meditations, services, and, if time permits, individual counseling. Days of Service: The care for the buildings and grounds is done by devotees on a volunteer basis. Once a month, usually the first Saturday of the month, we have a day of service where devotees care for the buildings and grounds. The morning of activity is followed by a vegetarian lunch.

item.title: Additional Info
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded:
Listed below are some details for the various services as well as additional information on the Houston Center.

Sunday Service

Silence: Before and after service in the chapel devotees may be meditating. For this reason and to show respect for the sanctuary, we ask that silence be maintained in the sanctuary. Although talking is permitted in the foyer, please do so in a low voice. Pranam: Once you reach your seat in the chapel, it is customary to show respect by pranamming (fold the hands in front of the heart) the altar and the picture of Paramahansa Yogananda before sitting. A pranam is also used as a greeting between devotees. It symbolizes bowing to God that dwells in the person you are greeting. If you arrive late for Sunday service: Please do not enter the chapel during a prayer, the affirmation, or a meditation. Wait in the foyer until the usher indicates you may enter. Once you enter the chapel, please sit near the back. Chanting: Devotional chanting is a part of every SRF service. Chant books are in the holder on the back of the chair in front of you. There are two books — a blue and a pink. The blue book contains the chants normally used during a reading service. The pink book contains additional chants and bhajans that may be used during services as well. The book and page number are announced before a chant.

Meditation Services

The Houston Center holds a number of Meditation services. All are welcome to attend. Most of the meditations are open, which means you may enter and leave quietly at any time. Some meditation services  have restrictions on entering. Sunday Meditation Service (10  – 10:45 AM): In order to maintain an atmosphere of stillness, the chapel will  be closed for entry after the opening chant (around 10:10 AM). If you arrive after the opening chant, you are welcome to meditate in the foyer. Thursday Night Meditation (7:30 – 9:30 PM, 7-10 PM the first Thursday of the month): The meditation is open.  You may enter or leave quietly at any time. Saturday All-day Meditation (9 AM – 4 PM on the fourth Saturday of the month): There are guided and unguided meditations. The unguided meditations are open. The guided meditations are not — you may enter or leave only during chants or readings. The quarterly newsletter will indicate if the meditation is guided or unguided. Saturday Afternoon Meditation (Noon – 3 PM on Saturdays when the chapel is not in use.  Generally all but the first and fourth Saturdays of the month): The meditation is open.  You may enter or leave quietly at any time. Commemorative Service Meditation (7 - 7:50 PM): The meditation is open.  You may enter or leave quietly at any time. New Year's Eve Meditation (6 – 8 PM): The meditation is open.  You may enter or leave quietly at any time. Good Friday Meditation (6 - 8 PM): The meditation is open.  You may enter or leave quietly at any time. Special Meditations: The dates for the all-day meditations for Christmas and Yogananda's birthday vary from year to year. They also have specials rules concerning entry. The dates are announced well in advance and are in the newsletter. A sheet listing the procedures for each is available at the chapel several weeks before the meditation. Attire: For long meditations it is recommended to wear loose fitting, comfortable clothes. Please avoid clothes that might make noise when you move, such as a nylon jacket. Perfume: Self-Realization Fellowship discourages the use of perfumes or other strong scents during services, especially long meditations. Some people have an allergic reaction, which would affect their ability to concentrate. If you have a cold: Self-Realization Fellowship asks that you do not attend a meditation service if you have a cold. Please tune into the service by meditating at home. Coughing: If you feel you are going to cough or do cough during a meditation service, please leave the sanctuary as soon and as quietly as possible. Kriya: If you have the Kriya technique, please remember to practice it quietly. Ideally Kriya is practiced so that you can hear it, but the person sitting next to you cannot. Mahamudra: If you have the Kriya technique and wish to practice the mahamudra exercise before a group meditation, please do so in private. Generally the Sunday school building will be open, where you will be able to find a suitable place to practice the exercise.

Commemorative Service

Flowers: Attendees are asked to bring a flower or flowers for use in the ceremony. If there is any wrapping or ribbons on the flowers, please remove them. Also do not place the flowers on the floor nor smell them, "stealing" the fragrance to be offered to the master. Donations: If you are financially able, bring a donation in an envelope. These donations are sent directly to Mother Center (the international headquarters in Los Angeles, CA). Make checks payable to Self-Realization Fellowship. The donation and the flowers are given during the ceremony. You will be directed when to offer them.

Memorial Services

Occasionally we hold a memorial service for one who has made the transition to another plane. The service is held immediately following the Sunday reading service. Everyone is encouraged to attend, even if you do not know the person in question. The vibrations of peace and love will be guided by God and Guru to the departed. We urge everyone to attend.

Common Terms

Master: You often hear devotees refer to Paramahansa Yogananda, or one of our other gurus, as Master. This is not used in the sense of "master" and "subordinate." Rather it is a title of respect bestowed on one who has mastered him or herself and is therefore able to lead others to the state of self-mastery. The Suffix "-ji": The suffix –ji (pronounced jee) is sometimes appended to a name or title to show respect. Yogananda may be referred to as Yoganandaji or Guruji. A monastic may be addressed as brotherji or sisterji, etc. Jai Guru: Literally means "hail Guru."  It is sometimes used as a salutation or exclamation by devotees.

Monastics

Self-Realization Fellowship has separate monastic orders for men and women. They reside in ashrams located at Mother Center and certain temples. The monastics take vows dedicating their lives to the service of God and Guru. Monks: There are three levels of monks. Those who have recently joined the ashram are referred to as postulants and dress in blue. Next are brahmacharis who dress in yellow. And finally there are brothers who wear ochre (golden) robes. Nuns: There are parallel levels for women — postulants, brahmacharinis, and sisters. They wear blue, yellow, or ochre as well.

item.title: Brief History
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded:
A Brief History of the Houston Center

In the summer of 1972 Self-Realization Fellowship invited devotees from Texas and adjoining states to meetings chaired by a Brother Mokshananda at St. Anthony's Hotel in San Antonio, Texas. During the meetings, four devotees from Houston connected. After returning to Houston, they began meeting in private homes for meditations. This was the beginning of a Self-Realization Fellowship group in Houston. They continued "house hopping" for several years until the mid-seventies when they began meeting in rental facilities, "The Blue Door Chapel" and later the "Yellow Brick Road." Various groups used both facilities, so members had to set up before each service and then take everything down afterwards. This went on for several years. Then in the late seventies two devotees purchased a church on Fulton Street which they turned into a daycare center. They offered a portion of the building to the group as a permanent meeting place. For the next sixteen years devotees met at the Fulton Street facility. Interestingly the building is situated between the streets Luther and Burbank. Luther Burbank, the great botanist, was a close friend of Paramahansa Yogananda. The Autobiography of a Yogi is dedicated to him. Over the years the devotees put a great deal of effort into remodeling the chapel and fitting out a Sunday school room. Two skilled members of the group fashioned a beautiful altar that is still used in the present chapel. Eventually the devotees who owned the facility moved out of state, selling the daycare center. The new owners allowed the group to rent the space used for services and Sunday school. In December of 2001 the group arranged with Mother Center to create a building fund for the eventual purchase of a permanent home. A pledge drive was started and funds began to accumulate. In 2004 a member noticed an ad for a church in the Garden Oaks area of Houston. After visits by members and consultations with Mother Center the property was purchased on June 16th, 2004. The Houston group finally  had its own home. There are four buildings on the property — the chapel; a former residence that now houses the Sunday school rooms, the parent-and-infant room, the kitchen, and the multipurpose room; a mobile building that serves as the office and storage area; and a tool shed. The chapel was useable but not ideally suited for SRF services. The residence also needed considerable work. A major remodeling project began in January of 2005 and continued for a total of ten months, the work being done by devotees. The chapel was officially dedicated on November 5th, 2005 by Brother Vijayananda and Bramachari Lynn. In the subsequent years, attendance at services and Sunday school substantially increased. In 2019 an anonymous donor gave a large sum to the Houston Center to purchase land and build a new chapel, which will accommodate the needs of our growing group.

item.title: Commemorative Services
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded:
Special services are held each year to honor the Self-Realization Fellowship gurus. They commemorate significant life events of each of the gurus. There are eight such services annually and are celebrated by SRF groups throughout the world.
Each commemorative ceremony consists of prayers, short meditations, chanting, readings on the life and teachings of the master who is being celebrated, and a flower ceremony. The service lasts approximately one hour. For those who wish to prepare spiritually for the ceremony, there is an hour-long meditation preceding the commemorative service. This meditation is open, and one can come and go quietly at any time.
Devotees are asked to bring a flower, which will be used during the flower ceremony. It is a symbol of devotion to God and the SRF Gurus. In addition one is asked to bring a monetary donation in an envelope as a symbol of loyalty and faithfulness to the cause of Self-Realization Fellowship. These donations are forwarded to Mother Center (International headquarters in Los Angeles, CA) for the sharing of these sacred teachings with truth-seeking souls.
These ceremonies are sacred and a beautiful expression of devotion toward the Gurus of Self-Realization Fellowship. Paramahansa Yogananda said the following of the birthday of a master (which applies to all the special days):
"Celebration of the birthday of a God-realized soul should not be belittled as a merely social ceremony. It is a deeply spiritual occasion on which the vibrations of blessing from an illumined master are stronger than on other days in the year, because in the astral world, also, a celebration is taking place. Devotees who attend these birthday ceremonies with the right attitude will reap spiritual benefits and will find their high resolutions strengthened." -Paramahansa Yogananda
All are urged to attend these beautiful and spiritually uplifting ceremonies. They are an integral part of the many reading and meditations services provided by the Houston Center.
The annual commemorative services are: • Birth of Paramahansa Yogananda — January 5th • Mahasamadhi of Paramahansa Yogananda — March 7th • Mahasamadhi of Swami Sri Yukteswar — March 9th • Birth of Swami Sri Yukteswar — May 10th • Babaji Day — July 25th • Janmashtami (Birth of Lord Krishna) — Aug/Sept (based on lunar calendar) • Mahasamadhi of Lahiri Mahasaya — September 26th • Birth of Lahiri Mahasaya — September 30th
In addition, we hold an all-day Christmas Meditation on a Saturday in December commemorating the birth of Lord Jesus. In early January there is a second all-day meditation honoring the birth of Paramahansa Yogananda. The meditations include periods of readings pertinent to the occasion as well as special music. Periods of meditation last from 30 to 45 minutes.

item.title: Volunteer Opportunities
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded: All activities and events organized by the Houston Center are done by dedicated devotees and we always welcome new volunteers. Listed below are some areas where there are opportunities to serve. Housekeeping: Cleaning of the chapel and other buildings to ensure an inviting atmosphere for meditation and other activities. Maintenance: Assure the proper operation of the various mechanical systems on the property, such as replacing AC filter, light bulbs, etc. We are always looking for people with handyman skills. Grounds: Keeping the chapel grounds clean and presentable. Flowers: Help arrange flowers for Sunday services and special events. Juice Socials: Help with the preparation and cleanup of the weekly juice socials, which follow the Sunday services. Assistance is also welcome at the periodic potlucks. Special skills such as bookkeeping/accounting, website management, landscaping, A/V, photography, etc. are always welcome. Once a person becomes more familiar with SRF by subscribing to the lessons and practicing the meditation techniques, there are other service opportunities, such as Sunday school, ushering, bookroom, kirtan group, greeting, and service reading. If you are interested in volunteering, please click here to fill out the volunteer sign-up sheet.

item.title: Literature
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded: The best source of information for current events at the Houston Center is our quarterly newsletter. Click here to view the most recent edition. Click here to subscribe and have it delivered to your inbox. Two pamphlets published by Self-Realization Fellowship are especially instructive. "Undreamed of Possibilities" serves as an introduction to Self-Realization Fellowship, outlining the tremendous spiritual treasures within each of us. "Worldwide Prayer Circle" focuses the prayers of SRF devotees around the world to enhance peace and overcome negativity. Both booklets are free of charge and available at the chapel. Also available free of charge at the chapel is the trifold "Group Meditation Guidelines." It gives the procedures and tips for meditating in a group.   In addition our group has a library located in the Sunday School building where you can check out SRF books, CDs, and DVDs for 2 weeks. You may also wish to visit the Houston Center bookstore located in the foyer of the chapel to explore SRF books, magazines, CDs, and DVDs for purchase. Please visit http://bookstore.yoganandasrf.org for a complete listing of publications and other material offered by Self-Realization Fellowship.

item.title: Lessons
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded:
Self-Realization Fellowship Lessons

Paramahansa Yogananda viewed the Self-Realization Fellowship Lessons as the very core of the teachings he was ordained to bring to the world as a special spiritual dispensation for the coming global civilization. In his talks and writings printed in his many acclaimed books for the public, Paramahansaji offers a wealth of practical guidance for spiritual living — how to live joyfully and successfully amidst the unceasing challenges and opportunities in this world of change. The Self-Realization Fellowship Lessons are for those who want to learn to convert that inspiration into a daily spiritual practice. The Lessons are unique among Paramahansa Yogananda’s published works, in that they give his step-by-step instructions in the yoga techniques of meditation, concentration, and energization that he taught, including Kriya Yoga. The Lessons are available for home study, one being mailed from the International Headquarter every two weeks.  They may also be viewed in digital format.  To apply for the lessons, click here.

item.title: Autobiography
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded:
Autobiography of a Yogi by Paramahansa Yogananda

Named one of the 100 Best Spiritual Books of the Twentieth Century, Paramahansa Yogananda’s remarkable life story takes you on an unforgettable exploration of the world of saints and yogis, science and miracles, death and resurrection. With soul-satisfying wisdom and endearing wit, he illuminates the deepest secrets of life and the universe — opening our hearts and minds to the joy, beauty, and unlimited spiritual potentials that exist in the lives of every human being. It incorporates all of his wishes for the final text including extensive material he added after the original 1946 edition and a final chapter on the closing years of his life.  It is available in our chapel bookstore in paperback, hardback, and audio editions.

item.title: The New HCSRF Website
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded:
As you might have noticed if you are familiar with our previous website, our new website has had a complete overhaul that includes a lot of great functionality.  New features include:
  1. The ability to subscribe and unsubscribe to our weekly announcements and quarterly newsletters.
  2. Newcomers that wish to volunteer may fill out the volunteer sign-up form on the Volunteer page.
  3. The contact information now has an interactive map for directions to our center, as well as an email form to send email directly to HCSRF.
  4. Several links are provided to more Self-Realization Fellowship online material in the Resources section, including a new FAQ page.
  5. The Houston Center now has an online calendar that will be updated regularly with details of upcoming events
  6. Last but not least, the site has integration with the Houston Center's Facebook page.
We encourage you to browse the new site and let us know your thoughts!  Do you have any ideas that you think could improve this website?  If so, please send an email to webmaster@srfhouston.org. In Divine Friendship, The Houston Center of Self-Realization Fellowship

wp:comment.wp:comment_content: Thanks to all who labored to make this website a very useful one.
It was our pleasure, Patrick. We are glad you like the new website.

item.title: Introducción
item.dc:creator: grehman
item.content:encoded:
Introducción al Centro de Houston 3425 Golf Drive, Houston, TX 77018-6225 Teléfono: 713-262-7272. http://www.srfhouston.org Correo electrónico: info@srfhouston.org

Bienvenido al Centro de Houston. El centro forma parte de Self-Realization Fellowship, una organización religiosa sin fines de lucro con sede internacional en Los Ángeles, C A. Self-Realization Fellowship fue fundada en 1920 por Paramahansa Yogananda con el propósito de difundir Kriya Yoga, una técnica científica definitiva para alcanzar una experiencia personal directa de Dios. A través de su servicio y enseñanzas en todo el mundo, Self-Realization Fellowship busca despertar una mayor comprensión de la armonía subyacente en todas las religiones verdaderas, y una expresión más completa en este mundo del amor cuando las personas se dan cuenta de su unidad con Dios. Las lecciones de SRF están disponibles para aquellos que deseen estudiar las enseñanzas. El centro cuenta con una serie de servicios y actividades, que se enumeran a continuación.

Domingo Servicio : Cada Domingo hay servicio en la capilla de 11:00 am hasta el mediodía. Incluye períodos de canto, meditaciones cortas, lecturas de la Biblia y Bhagavad Gita, y una lectura tomada de los escritos de Paramahansa Yogananda. Está precedido por un servicio de meditación de 10 : 00 a 10:45 AM .

Escuela ominical: la escuela dominical para niños de 4 a 12 años se lleva a cabo en el edificio de la escuela dominical al mismo tiempo que el servicio dominical. Para los niños más pequeños tenemos una habitación Infantil en el edificio de la escuela dominical. El servicio del domingo se transmite por una televisión de circuito cerrado para que los padres puedan ver el servicio mientras que esten con los niños. El primer domingo del mes, el grupo de adolescentes (de 13 a 18 años) se reúne de 11:00 a 12:00.

Librería: una librería se encuentra fuera del vestíbulo en la capilla. Libros de SRF, CDs, DVDs, fotos y varios de los suministros de meditación están disponibles para la venta. Además de dinero en efectivo o cheques , tarjetas de crédito son aceptadas . La librería está abierta entre la meditación dominical y el servicio dominical y después del servicio dominical.

Servicios de meditación: En adición a la meditación realizada antes del servicio de lectura en Domingo, tenemos una serie de servicios en el capilla dedicados exclusivamente a la meditación. Todos los jueves por la noche se lleva a cabo un servicio de meditación de 7:30 a 9:30 (7:00 a 10:00 el primer jueves del mes) . Cada cuarto sábado de cada mes hay un día de meditación comenzando las 9 a.m.- 4 p.m. . La capilla está abierta de mediodía a 3 PM para la meditación los sábados cuando la capilla no está en uso. Hay una serie de meditaciones especiales durante él año – Noche antes del Año Nuevo, Viernes Santo, una meditación de Navidad durante todo el día, y una meditación especial de toda el día en el mes de Enero en honor a Paramahansa Yogananda. Todos son bienvenidos.

Lección de Estudio: Todos los lunes por la noche 7:00-8:00 p.m. hay un estudio de la lección grupo en la capilla. Los devotos se turnan para leer un párrafo de una lección n SRF. Despues de cada lección hay una breve meditación para asimilar esa parte de la enseñanza. El grupo de estudio es seguido por una meditación de 8:00 a 9:00 . El grupo de estudio de lecciones está abierto a todos los estudiantes de lecciones de SRF .

Bhagavad Gita Grupo de Estudio: En el tercer Domingo, cada mes devotos se reúnen en la capilla a las 12:30 durante una hora para leer de Dios conversa con Arjuna - Paramahansa Yogananda traducción y commentario de el Bhagavad Gita . El formato es el mismo que el Grupo de Estudio de lecciónes . Todos son bienvenidos.

Servicios Commemorativos: Ocho veces al año en el cumpleaños o anniversariode de uno de nuestros gurús, tenemos un servicio especial en la capilla comenzando a las 8:00 PM. Hay varios meditaciónes cortas, cantos, y una lectura relacionada con el gurú de quien se celebra. Hay una ceremonia de flores donde cada devoto coloca una flor y una donación frente a la imagen del Maestro. A los que están familiarizados con la relacion de guru-discípulo son invitados a asistir. El servicio es precedido por una meditación - de 07:00 a las 7:45 AM.  Los servicios son:

5 de Enero…..Cumpleaños de Paramahansa Yogananda 7de Marzo….. Mahasamadhi* de Paramahansa Yogananda 9 de Marzo….. Mahasamadhi* de Swami Sri Yukteswar 10 de Mayo…..Cumpleaños de Swami Sri Yukteswar 25 de Julio…..Día de Babaji La fecha varía…..Janmashtami(cumpleaños del Señor Krishna) 26 de Septiembre……Mahasamadhi* de Lahiri Mahasaya 30 de de Septiembre…..Cumpleaños de Lahiri Mahasaya

* Mahasamadhi es la unión del alma con el Infinito durante la salida final de un yogui realizado por Dios del cuerpo físico.

Retiros: dos veces al año reservamos habitaciones en la Villa de Matel en Houston para un retiro silencioso. El retiro comienza el jueves (llegada Viernes opcional) y continúa hasta el domingo por la mañana. Las habitaciones y los alimentos se proporcionan en forma de donación. Un número de meditaciones grupo son programadas y se muestran vídeos SRF. Tambien hay bastante tiempo libre para meditaciones privadas , para dar un paseo por los jardines , o para visitor la capilla.

Reuniones Sociales: Después de servicios de Domingo hay sociales en el edificio de la escuela dominical. Se proporcionan jugos y refrescos ligeros . Para la Pascua, Acción de Gracias , y Navidiad nos mantenemos unas comidas vegetarianas en la escuela dominical despues de los servicios del Domingo. Los eventos sociales y las comidas compartidas son una excelente manera de conocer a otros devotos y aprender más sobre el Centro de Houston y SRF.

Jovenes –de -Corazón Grupo: Un grupo de jóvenes y tambien adultos jóvenes de corazón se reúnen para diversas actividades, como picnics . Es una buena manera de conocer a otros jóvenes que están en el camino SRF.

Visitas monásticas: Una vez o dos veces al año somos bendecidos con una visita de los monjes SRF de la Madre Centro en Los Angeles, CA. Estas visitas inclyuen meditación en grupo, servicios y eventos especiales, y , si el tiempo lo permite, consulta individual.

Días de servicio: La attencion para los edificios y los jardines se realiza por los devotos voluntarios. Una vez al mes, por lo general el primer Sabado del mes , tenemos una dia de servicio donde los devotos se preocupan por los edificios y terrenos. La mañana de la actividad es seguida por un almuerzo vegetariano.

item.title: Lecciones de Self-Realization Fellowship
item.dc:creator: grehman
item.content:encoded: Paramahansa Yogananda vio las Lecciones de Self-Realization Fellowship como el núcleo de las enseñanzas que fue ordenado para llevar al mundo como una dispensación espiritual especial para la próxima civilización global. En sus charlas y escritos impresos en sus muchos libros aclamados para el público, Paramahansaji ofrece una gran cantidad de orientación práctica para la vida espiritual: cómo vivir con alegría y éxito en medio de los incesantes desafíos y oportunidades en este mundo de cambio. Las lecciones de Self-Realization Fellowship son para aquellos que quieren aprender a convertir esa inspiración en una práctica spiritual diaria. Las lecciones son únicos entre los trabajos publicados de Paramahansa Yogananda, en el sentido de que dan sus instrucciones paso a paso en las técnicas yoga de meditación, concentración y energía que enseñó, incluso el Kriya Yoga. Las lecciones están disponibles para estudio en el hogar, una se envía por correo desde la sede internacional cada dos semanas. También se pueden ver en formato digital. Para solicitar las lecciones, haga clic aquí.

item.title: Literatura
item.dc:creator: grehman
item.content:encoded: La mejor fuente de información para eventos actuales en el Centro de Houston es nuestro boletín trimestral. Haga clic aquí para ver la edición más reciente. Haga clic aquí para suscribirse y enviarlo a su email.   Dos folletos publicados por Self-Realization Fellowship son especialmente instructivos. "Undreamed of Possibilities" sirve como una introducción a Self-Realization Fellowship, que describe los tremendos tesoros espirituales dentro de cada uno de nosotros. El "Círculo de Oración Mundial" enfoca las oraciones de los devotos de SRF alrededor del mundo para mejorar la paz y superar la negatividad. Ambos folletos son gratuitos y están disponibles en la capilla. También está disponible de forma gratuita en la capilla la triple "Guía de meditación grupal.” Ofrece los procedimientos y consejos para meditar en grupo.   Además, nuestro grupo tiene una biblioteca ubicada en el edificio de la Escuela Dominical donde puede pedir prestado libros, CD y DVD de SRF durante 2 semanas. También puede visitar la librería del Centro de Houston ubicada en el vestíbulo de la capilla para explorar los libros, revistas, CD y DVD de SRF para comprar. Por favor, visite http://bookstore.yogananda-srf.org/ para obtener una lista completa de las publicaciones y otros materiales ofrecidos por Self-Realization Fellowship.

item.title: Bienvenido
item.dc:creator: grehman
item.content:encoded:
Gracias por visitar el sitio web de Self-Realization Fellowship de Houston. Espero que se unan a nosotros para explorar las enseñanzas intemporales de Paramahansa Yogananda y reclamar su unidad con Dios, siempre nueva alegría, amor y paz. Es a través de las técnicas de meditación enseñadas por Self-Realization Fellowship que podemos descubrir esta conciencia divina que se esconde dentro de cada uno de nosotros.
Las técnicas de meditación se dan en una serie de lecciones de estudio en el hogar enviadas desde la sede internacional cada dos semanas. De este modo paso a paso se puede avanzar en el camino de la auto-realización a través de la práctica de la técnicas de meditación , que culminan con la Kriya Yoga. Paramahansa Yogananda a menudo se refería al camino del Kriya Yoga, con sus técnicas científicas de meditación, como "la carretera hacia el Infinito". Encontró que el camino del Kriya Yoga era el método más eficaz para alcanzar el objetivo más elevado de la religión, y de hecho la vida misma: unión con la felicidad.
Nuestro centro tiene una variedad de servicios abiertos a todos. Cada uno incluye oraciones, lecturas de las obras de Paramahansa Yogananda, cantos y, lo más importante, meditación. Además, tenemos un programa de escuela dominical para los niños pequeños y un grupo de adolescentes para los mayores. También hay eventos sociales donde puedes conocer a devotos y aprender más sobre Self-Realization Fellowship y el Centro de Houston.
Por favor continúe explorando nuestro sitio web. Encontrará información detallada sobre nuestros servicios, una breve historia de nuestro grupo, donde conseguir nuestro boletín trimestral, la literatura que está disponible, incluyendo el clásico spiritual de Paramahansa Yogananda, Autobiografía de un Yogui, y la forma de suscribirse a la importantísima Lecciones de Self-Realization Fellowship.
Esperamos que nuestro sitio web a sido informativo.
En la amistad divina,
Self-Realization Fellowship de Houston

item.title: Oportunidades para voluntarios
item.dc:creator: grehman
item.content:encoded: Todas las actividades y eventos organizados por el Centro de Houston son realizados por devotos dedicados y siempre damos la bienvenida a nuevos voluntarios. A continuación se enumeran algunas áreas donde hay  oportunidades para servir. Limpieza: Limpieza de la capilla y otros edificios para garantizar un ambiente acogedor para la meditación y otras actividades. Mantenimiento: Asegure el correcto funcionamiento de los diversos sistemas mecánicos en la propiedad, como el reemplazo del filtro de AC, bombillas, etc. Siempre estamos buscando personas con habilidades de personal de mantenimiento. Terrenos: Mantener los terrenos de la capilla limpios y presentables. Flores: Ayuda a organizar flores para los servicios dominicales y eventos especiales . Eventos Sociales: Ayuda con la preparación y limpieza de los eventos sociales semanales de jugo, que siguen a los servicios dominicales. La asistencia también es bienvenida en las comidas periódicas. Las habilidades especiales como contabilidad, administración de sitios web, paisajismo, audio y video, fotografía, etc. siempre son bienvenidas. Una vez que una persona se familiariza con SRF al suscribirse a las lecciones y practicar las técnicas de meditación, hay otras oportunidades de servicio, como la escuela dominical, ser ujier, la sala de libros, el grupo de kirtan, saludador, y la lectura de servicio. Si está interesado en ser voluntario, haga clic aquí para completar la hoja de inscripción de voluntario.

item.title: Una Breve Historia del Centro de Houston
item.dc:creator: grehman
item.content:encoded:
En el verano de 1972, Self-Realization Fellowship invitó a los devotos de Texas y de los estados vecinos a las reuniones presididas por un hermano Mokshananda en el hotel St. Anthony's en San Antonio, Texas. Durante las reunions, cuatro devotos de Houston se conectaron. Después de regresar a Houston, comenzaron a reunirse en casas privadas para meditar. Este fue el comienzo de un grupo de Self-Realization Fellowship en Houston. Continuaron "yendo de casa en casa" durante varios años hasta mediados de los setentas cuando comenzaron a reunirse en instalaciones familiares, "La Capilla de la Puerta Azul" y más tarde en el "Camino de ladrillos amarillos". Varios grupos usaron ambas instalaciones, por lo que los miembros tuvieron que establecerse antes de cada servicio y luego quitar todo después. Esto continuó por varios años.
Luego, a fines de los setentas, dos devotos compraron una iglesia en la calle Fulton que convirtieron en una guardería. Ofrecieron una parte del edificio al grupo como lugar de reunión permanente. Durante los siguientes dieciséis años, los devotos se reunieron en las instalaciones de Fulton Street. Interesantamente, el edificio está situado entre las calles de Luther y Burbank . Luther Burbank, un botánico famoso, era un amigo cercano de Paramahansa Yogananda. La Autobiografía de un Yogui está dedicada a él.
Durante los años, los devotos pusieron una gran cantidad de esfuerzo en la remodelación de la capilla y el acondicionamiento de una escuela dominical. Dos miembros del grupo construyeron un hermoso altar que todavía se utiliza en la presente capilla. Finalmente, los devotos que eran dueños de la facilidad se movieron del estado y vendieron la guarderia. Los nuevos propietarios permitieron al grupo alquilar el espacio para utlizarlo para los servicios y la escuela dominical.
En diciembre de 2001, el grupo acordó con el Centro Madre crear un fondo de construcción para la compra eventual de una vivienda permanente. Se inició una campaña de compromiso y los fondos comenzaron a acumularse. En 2004, un miembro notó un anuncio de una iglesia en el área de Garden Oaks de Houston. Después de ser visto por los miembros y consultado con el Centro Madre, la propiedad fue adquirida el 16 de Junio, 2004. El grupo de Houston finalmente tuvo su propia casa.
Hay cuatro edificios en la propiedad: la capilla; una antigua residencia que ahora alberga las salas de la escuela dominical, la sala de padres e hijos, la cocina y la sala de usos múltiples; un edificio móvil que sirve como la oficina y almacenamiento de área; y un cobertizo para herramientas. La capilla era utilizable pero no era ideal para los servicios de SRF. La residencia también necesitaba un trabajo considerable. Un importante proyecto de remodelación comenzó en Enero de 2005 y continuó durante un total de diez meses, el trabajo realizado por devotos.
La capilla fue dedicada oficialmente de Noviembre 5 de 2005 por el hermano Vijayananda y Bramachari Lynn. En los años posteriores, la asistencia a los servicios y la escuela dominical sustancialmente aumentado.
En 2019 un anónimo donante dio una gran suma a el Centero de Houston para comprar terrenos y construir una nueva capilla, que tendrá espacio para las necesidades de nuestro grupo que sigue creciendo y son cada vez mayor.

item.title: Servicios conmemorativos
item.dc:creator: grehman
item.content:encoded:
Cada año se realizan servicios especiales para honrar a los gurús de la Self-Realization Fellowship. Conmemoran importantes eventos de la vida de cada uno de los gurús. Hay ocho de estos servicios anualmente y son celebrados por grupos de SRF en todo el mundo.
Cada ceremonia conmemorativa consiste en oraciones, meditaciones cortas, cantos, lecturas sobre la vida y las enseñanzas del maestro que se celebra, y una ceremonia de flores. El servicio dura aproximadamente una hora. Para aquellos que desean prepararse espiritualmente para la ceremonia, hay una meditación de una hora que precede al servicio conmemorativo. Esta meditación es abierta, y uno puede ir y venir en silencio en cualquier momento.
Se pide a los devotos que traigan una flor, que se usará durante la ceremonia de la flor. Es un símbolo de devoción a Dios y a los Gurus de SRF. Además, se le pide a uno que traiga una donación monetaria en un sobre como símbolo de lealtad y fidelidad a la causa de la Self-Realization Fellowship. Estas donaciones se envían al Centro Madre (sede internacional en Los Ángeles, CA) para compartir estas enseñanzas sagradas con las almas que buscan la verdad.
Estas ceremonias son sagradas y una hermosa expresión de devoción hacia los Gurús de la Comunidad de Self-Realiztion. Paramahansa Yogananda dijo lo siguiente del cumpleaños de un maestro (que se aplica a todos los días especiales):
"La celebración del cumpleaños de un alma realizada por Dios no debe ser menospreciada como una simple ceremonia social. Es una ocasión profundamente espiritual en la cual las vibraciones de bendición de un maestro iluminado son más fuertes que en otros días del año, porque en el En el mundo astral, también, se está celebrando una celebración. Los devotos que asisten a estas ceremonias de cumpleaños con la actitud correcta cosecharán beneficios espirituales y verán fortalecidas sus altas resoluciones ". -Paramahansa Yogananda
Se insta a todos a asistir a estas ceremonias hermosas y espiritualmente edificantes. Son una parte integral de los muchos servicios de lectura y meditación proporcionados por el Centro de Houston.
Los servicios conmemorativos anuales son:
• Nacimiento de Paramahansa Yogananda - 5 de Enero • Mahasamadhi de Paramahansa Yogananda - 7 de Marzo • Mahasamadhi de Swami Sri Yukteswar - 9 de Marzo • Nacimiento de Swami Sri Yukteswar - 10 de Mayo • Día de Babaji - 25 de Julio • Janmashtami (nacimiento del Señor Krishna) - Agosto / Septiembre (basado en el calendario lunar) • Mahasamadhi de Lahiri Mahasaya - 26 de Septiembre • Nacimiento de Lahiri Mahasaya - 30 de Septiembre
Además, realizamos una meditación Navideña durante todo el día un sábado de diciembre para conmemorar el nacimiento del Señor Jesús. A principios de Enero hay una segunda meditación de todo el día en honor al nacimiento de Paramahansa Yogananda. Las meditaciones incluyen períodos de lecturas pertinentes a la ocasión, así como música especial. Los períodos de meditación duran de 30 a 45 minutos.

item.title: Autobiografía de un Yogui por Paramahansa Yogananda
item.dc:creator: grehman
item.content:encoded: Nombrado uno de los 100 mejores libros espirituales del siglo XX, la notable historia de vida de Paramahansa Yogananda lo lleva a una exploración inolvidable del mundo de los santos y yoguis, la ciencia y  los milagros, la muerte y la resurrección. Con una sabiduría que satisface el alma y un ingenio entrañable, ilumina los secretos más profundos de la vida y del universo, abriendo nuestros corazones y mentes a la alegría, la belleza y los potenciales espirituales ilimitados que existen en la vida de cada ser humano.  Incorpora todos sus deseos para el texto final, incluido el extenso material que agregó después de la edición original de 1946 y un capítulo final sobre los últimos años de su vida. Está disponible en nuestra librería de la  capilla en edición de bolsillo, tapa dura y audio.

item.title: Información Adicional
item.dc:creator: grehman
item.content:encoded: A continuación se enumeran algunos detalles de los diversos servicios, así como información adicional sobre el Centro de Houston. Servicios dominicales Silencio: antes y después del servicio en la capilla, los devotos pueden estar meditando. Por esta razón y para mostrar respeto por el santuario, pedimos que se mantenga el silencio en el santuario. Aunque se permite hablar en el vestíbulo, hágalo en voz baja. Pranam: Una vez que llegue a su asiento en la capilla, es costumbre mostrar respeto al pranamming (doblar las manos frente al corazón) el altar y la imagen de Paramahansa Yogananda antes de sentarse. Un pranam también se usa como saludo entre los devotos. Simboliza inclinarse ante Dios que habita en la persona que está saludando. Si llega tarde al servicio dominical: no ingrese a la capilla durante una oración, la afirmación o una meditación. Espere en el vestíbulo hasta que el acomodador indique que puede ingresar. Una vez que ingrese a la capilla, siéntese cerca de la parte de atrás. Canto: El canto devocional es parte de cada servicio SRF. Los libros de canto están en el soporte en el respaldo de la silla frente a usted. Hay dos libros: uno azul y uno rosa. El libro azul contiene los cantos que normalmente se usan durante un servicio de lectura. El libro rosa contiene cantos y bhajans adicionales que también pueden usarse durante los servicios. El libro y el número de página se anuncian antes de un canto. Servicios de meditacion El Centro de Houston tiene una serie de servicios de meditación. Todos son bienvenidos para asistir. La mayoría de las meditaciones están abiertas, lo que significa que puede entrar y salir en silencio en cualquier momento. Algunos servicios de meditación tienen restricciones para entrar. Servicio de meditación dominical (10 - 10:45 AM): para mantener una atmósfera de quietud, la capilla estará cerrada para entrar después del canto de apertura (alrededor de las 10:10 a.m.). Si llegas después del canto de apertura, puedes meditar en el vestíbulo. Meditación del jueves por la noche (7:30 - 9:30 PM, 7-10 PM el primer jueves del mes): La meditación está abierta. Puede entrar o salir en silencio en cualquier momento. Meditación del sábado durante todo el día (9 AM. - 4 PM. El cuarto sábado del mes): hay meditaciones guiadas y no guiadas. Las meditaciones no guiadas están abiertas. Las meditaciones guiadas no son: puede ingresar o salir solo durante los cantos o las lecturas. El boletín trimestral indicará si la meditación es guiada o no. Meditación de los sábados por la tarde (Mediodía - 3 PM. Los sábados cuando la capilla no está en uso. Generalmente todos menos el primer y cuarto sábado del mes): la meditación está abierta. Puede entrar o salir en silencio en cualquier momento. Servicio de meditación conmemorativa (7 - 7:50 PM): La meditación está abierta. Puede entrar o salir en silencio en cualquier momento. Meditación de Nochevieja (6 - 8 PM): la meditación está abierta. Puede entrar o salir en silencio en cualquier momento. Meditación del Viernes Santo (6 a 8 PM): La meditación está abierta. Puede entrar o salir en silencio en cualquier momento. Meditaciones especiales: las fechas de las meditaciones de todo el día para Navidad y el cumpleaños de Yogananda varían de un año a otro. También tienen reglas especiales sobre la entrada. Las fechas se anuncian con suficiente antelación y se encuentran en el boletín. Una hoja que enumera los procedimientos para cada uno está disponible en la capilla varias semanas antes de la meditación. Vestimenta: para meditaciones largas se recomienda usar ropa holgada y cómoda. Evite la ropa que pueda hacer ruido cuando se mueva, como una chaqueta de nylon. Perfume: Self-Realization Fellowship desalienta el uso de perfumes u otros olores fuertes durante los servicios, especialmente meditaciones largas. Algunas personas tienen una reacción alérgica, que afectaría su capacidad de concentración. Si tiene un resfriado: Self-Realization Fellowship le pide que no asista a un servicio de meditación si tiene un resfriado. Sintonice el servicio meditando en casa. Tos: Si siente que va a toser o toser durante un servicio de meditación, abandone el santuario lo antes y lo más silenciosamente posible. Kriya: Si tienes la técnica de Kriya, recuerda practicarla en silencio. Idealmente, se practica Kriya para que puedas escucharlo, pero la persona sentada a tu lado no puede. Mahamudra: Si tiene la técnica de Kriya y desea practicar el ejercicio de mahamudra antes de una meditación grupal, hágalo en privado. En general, el edificio de la escuela dominical estará abierto, donde podrá encontrar un lugar adecuado para practicar el ejercicio. Servicio conmemorativo Flores: Se pide a los asistentes que traigan una flor o flores para usar en la ceremonia. Si hay envolturas o cintas en las flores, quítelas. Tampoco coloque las flores en el piso ni las huela, "robando" la fragancia que se ofrecerá al maestro. Donaciones: si tiene capacidad financiera, traiga una donación en un sobre. Estas donaciones se envían directamente al Centro Madre (la sede internacional en Los Ángeles, CA). Haga los cheques a nombre de Self-Realization Fellowship. La donación y las flores.

Dear Members and Friends,

Mother Center has recently informed us Brahmachari Andy will be the new monastic counselor serving with our Houston Center. Br. Andy has been serving in Center Department for several years and works with many SRF groups and centers in the U.S.  Following is a note from Br. Jason’s email to the managing team highlighting this change:

"It has been a joy and pleasure serving with all of you!  The Houston Center deserves nothing but praise and gratitude for the wonderful spirit with which you carry on together, with Master’s ideals ever to the fore. Thank you for your friendship and kindness towards me.  I’m not going anywhere but just assuming responsibility for other meditation groups; sometimes we move groups from one monastic to another here in Center Department. Again, thank you so much for everything and keep up the good work!  Jai Guru!"

Until then, may the blessing of the Guru rest upon you

item.title: Bhagavad Gita Study Group
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded:
Dear Members and Friends,

We are happy to announce that the Center Department of Self-Realization Fellowship has approved our plans to initiate a study group of Paramahansa Yogananda's spiritual interpretation of the Bhagavad Gita - God Talks with Arjuna. This group is open to all members and friends who wish to read and meditate upon this monumental work. Our inaugural meeting will be held in the chapel on Sunday, August 25 as a prelude to Janmashtami, the birthday celebration of Bhagavan Krishna. We hope that you are able to attend.  More information about the meetings can be found below, or downloaded by clicking here.

Bhagavad Gita Study Group

Objective: to read and meditate upon Paramahansa Yogananda’s spiritual interpretation of the Bhagavad Gita, “God Talks with Arjuna” as a group. Contents: all verses in English and the spiritual interpretation that follows each verse; footnotes are to be excluded. Days and Time: On the 3rd Sunday of every month, from 1 pm to 2:30 pm; one hour is dedicated to actual readings and 30 minutes are dedicated to a closing meditation. Location: Houston Center chapel Format (see sample program below): similar to existing Lessons Study Group – read a paragraph or two aloud (depending on length), pause for a minute and then resume reading aloud. Short meditations of less than five minutes will be included every 15 minutes. Restrictions and Attendance: there will be no discussions or interpretations of the readings, as per SRF guidelines. Participation is open to everyone who accepts the previous restriction. Attendance is non-mandatory. Meetings will begin promptly at 1 pm with a prayer. Leadership: group will have a coordinator who will schedule a leader for every meeting on a rotational basis and who will maintain communication with the Managing Team. Leaders are voluntary and will guide the entire session and will assign volunteers to read. Leaders will also note beginning and end of section(s) read and will notify coordinator. Readers: members will rotate the scheduled paragraphs as indicated by the monthly leader. Anyone in attendance who has good command of the English language is welcome to read. Participation as readers is entirely voluntary. Attendees may silently follow the readings. Chapel copies: several copies of God Talks with Arjuna will be made available for chapel use only. Attendees are encouraged to bring their own copies or to purchase a set from the bookstore. Chapel copies may not be marked or underlined. Duration of the Group: group will meet until volumes I and II of God Talks with Arjuna are completed, beginning with the introduction. Upon completion, the group may vote to start a new round of Gita sessions or to begin with a different scriptural interpretation by Paramahansa Yogananda. Tentative Status: the above plan will remain tentative for a period of six months, after which adjustments may be made as per the group’s recommendation to the Managing Team.

Sample Program

1:00 – 1:05 pm:           Opening Prayer and meditation 1:05 - 1:10 pm:            Brief instructions and call for volunteers to read 1:10 – 1:25 pm:           Readings (15 minutes) 1:25 – 130 pm:            Meditation (5 minutes) 1:30 – 1:45 pm:           Readings (15 minutes) 1:45 – 1:50 pm:           Meditation (5 minutes) 1:50 – 2:00 pm:           Readings (10 minutes) 2:00 – 2:28 pm:           Meditation (28 minutes) 2:28 – 2:30 pm:           Closing Prayer

item.title: Austin Meditation Group - Monastic Visit, April 11-13, 2014.
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded:
Brother Ritananda and Brahmachari Andy from the Center Department will be visiting the Austin Meditation Group from Friday, April 11th to Sunday, April 13th. The Austin Meditation Group is inviting all members and friends of the Houston Center to attend the 3-day event. There will be workshop, energization exercises review, satsanga, kirtan chanting, guided meditation... The detail program of activities can be seen below. If you are planning to attend or would like to know more about the event, please contact David Doonan at djdoonan@gmail.com. 

Monastic Visit Agenda

item.title: Open House on Saturday May 3rd, 2014
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded: The Houston Center of Self-Realization Fellowship will be holding an open house on Saturday, May 3rd. You are invited to bring all family and friends to introduce to the teaching of Paramahansa Yogananda, author of the best-selling spiritual classic “Autobiography of a Yogi”. The Open House will feature devotional chanting, guided meditation and a video presentation “Experiencing God Within”. It will be held from 1pm to 4pm at our location on 3425 Golf drive, Houston TX 77018. All newcomers will receive a welcoming packet enclosing literature excerpts from Paramahansa Yogananda's writings and many additional items. The Open House program is as follows: 1:00 pm    Welcome 1:10 pm    Kirtan (devotional chanting) 1:40 pm    Guided Meditation 2:00 pm    Intermission 2:05 pm    Video presentation 3:10 pm    Refreshments

item.title: Monastic Outing Friday, Dec. 18th
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded: On Friday, December 18, we will be organizing an outing with Brother Kalyanananda & Br. Troy to visit the Battleship of Texas Historic Site and the San Jacinto Monument. We plan to meet at the Chapel around 8:30am on Friday, December 18  and will depart sharply at 9:00am. The entrance fee is $6 per person. We will have a picnic on the grounds after the site tour around Noon.  Everyone is encouraged to bring their own brown bag lunch. If you are interested in joining us for this outing with the Monastics, please fill out the sign-up form located in the chapel foyer so we can have the accurate head count to purchase group tickets in advance. If you have any questions about this outing, please contact Chetan Patel by emailing him at chetancpatel@hotmail.com.

item.title: Hurricane Harvey
item.dc:creator: HCSRF
item.content:encoded: In light of the threat that Hurricane Harvey poses to the Texas Coast and the City of Houston this weekend, Managing Team has decided to CANCEL all Houston Center activities beginning Saturday 8-26 through Monday 8-28.  This includes Sunday School and the Reading Service on Sunday 8-27. The safety of our devotees and guests is our paramount concern and we ask that everyone exercise tremendous caution in the next few days and minimize unnecessary travel.   We pray that all of you will be safe and sound as this storm passes. We will resume normal Center activities on Thursday August 31 for our evening meditation. In divine friendship, Houston Center of SRF

Hi Friends,
In the process of reducing our home library, we found a collection of pamphlets written by Roy Eugene Davis that my parents had for many years. Both my parents and my brother were practitioners of Kriya Yoga, having met Mr. Davis in Georgia and lived for many years at Kriyananda's Ananda Cooperative Community in northern California. We were going to give these to the Half-Price Book Store, but thought you might find them useful if you have a library. Please let me know if you would like us to bring them by. We live on the southwest side of Houston, only about 20-25 minutes from your center.
Sincerely, Stephen Haslam

Greetings Pastor and Staff,

My name is Claudell C. Cannady and I am a liaison between the local Boy Scout Council and Houston Schools. One of the most important parts of being a Scout is our Reverence to God. We typically partner with strong local churches and schools to start up and support local Cub Scout and Boy Scout Troops. We have several families in your area, that would like to start a local Cub Scout Pack, and I would like to determine if your congregation would be a great supporting partner. We have great support with our local District rep and and at this point I am only looking to have a conversation to see if it would be a good fit. If your congregation is not available, if you know of any others nearby that would greatly be appreciated.

Sincerely,
Claudell C Cannady

Unit Development

Sam Houston Area Council

BOY SCOUTS OF AMERICA

2225 North Loop West
Houston, TX 77008
C 832-707-0107

Hi,

My name is Mason Woods, and I am 22 years old. I am a recent college graduate, and I am back in Texas during this pandemic. I understand that you are no longer offering services, but I am interested in learning more about Kriya Yoga and the teachings of the SRF. I own a copy of Paramahansa Yogananda's autobiography, and I have briefly visited the SRF ashram in San Diego in high school. I am really looking for a community devoted to human enlightenment and to helping me grow spiritually.

I noticed that the SRF's international website (yogananda.org) was charging for access to the SRF's lessons. Is this true? As a recent college grad looking for work, I am limited in terms of my financial means, and to be completely open and honest, I am a little surprised that such lessons would have financial barriers if the goal is to raise human consciousness.

I have been quite fond of the little I know of Yogananda's teachings and perspectives about applying Kriya Yoga and yogic scripture to life. It would be great to learn more!

Thank you,
Mason

Hi,

Have you noticed that self-care seems to be a luxury reserved for the privileged? Even self-care practices that don’t cost a lot of money still require time that some people just aren’t able to spare.

I’ve been giving this a lot of thought lately, and I’ve come up with some great ways for those who are overworked and underpaid to work self-care into their lives without sacrificing a lot of time or money. I’d love to put together an article on how to make self-care accessible for everyone. I'd also be happy to feature your website within the piece!

If you think this type of piece is a good fit for your site, please let me know, and I’ll get started on a (free!) article for you!

Thank you!
Emma Grace Brown
Emmagracebrown.com
info@emmagracebrown.com

Hello! I am a Sam Houston State graduate student studying in the field of clinical mental health counseling. I am currently enrolled in a class exploring cross cultural issues and barriers and one of our assignments is to find an organization with a culture that I am unfamiliar with and provide some volunteer work. The purpose of the experience is to gain knowledge and appreciation of a culture other than my own and to reflect on how this experience aids in my future counseling work. As soon as I came across your organization, I knew I was definitely interested! I practice yoga and have done some meditation, but am interested in expanding my knowledge on how it contributes to mental health. I hope to incorporate holistic practices in my service as a future counselor. If you would please take my situation into consideration I would highly appreciate and value this experience. I do not mind volunteering in any area that you see fit for your organization; all I ask is that I may gain valuable insight on what this organization does and to expand my knowledge. I am available through contact email or phone. Thank you for reading this! Sincerely, Brittany Johnson

Dear SRF Temple/Center Administrator,

I am the coordinator of the NBL-Chinese translation team. We are recruiting additional translators for the project. Please kindly help distribute the e-mail below to your devotees. Let me know if you have any questions. Thanks!

______________________________________________________________

Translator (English -> Chinese) for New Basic Lessons

Dear SRF devotees,

As one major endeavor to spread the special dispensation that Guruji brought to the world, the SRF New Basic Lessons (NBL) are being translated into various languages, including Chinese — both Traditional (Taiwan) and Simplified (Mainland China).

We are pleased to inform you that the Chinese translation has been progressing as planned. However, in order to keep the progress and enable the Chinese lessons to be available to all Chinese truth seekers at its earliest possible time, we are reaching out for more devotees of translation skills.

If you are proficient in both English and Chinese, and if you would like to join forces with us as volunteer translators/checkers in this major endeavor, please respond to this email. Alternatively, if you know someone is, please help connect he/she with us.

Thank you for your attention and look forward to hearing from you!

Jai Guru,
Celine P. Halperin

from Encinitas
650-575-2800 (cell)
extradlifescience@gmail.com
